# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: concord-new-hampshire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The area was first settled by Europeans in 1659.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] On January 17, 1725, the Province of Massachusetts Bay granted the Concord area as the Plantation of Penacook, and it was incorporated on February 9, 1734, as the Town of Rumford.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Governor Benning Wentworth gave the city its current name in 1765 following a boundary dispute with the neighboring town of Bow; the name was meant to signify the new harmony between the two towns.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 1808, Concord was named the official seat of state government, and the State House was completed in 1819; it remains the oldest U.S. state capitol wherein the legislature meets in its original chambers.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is entirely within the Merrimack River watershed and the city is centered on the river.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The Merrimack runs from northwest to southeast through the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city's eastern boundary is formed by the Soucook River, which separates Concord from the town of Pembroke.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The Turkey River passes through the southwestern quarter of the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city consists of its downtown, including the North End and South End neighborhoods, along with the four villages of Penacook, Concord Heights, East Concord, and West Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Penacook sits along the Contoocook River, just before it flows into the Merrimack.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] As of 2020, the top employer in the city was the State of New Hampshire, and the largest private employer was Concord Hospital.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is home to the University of New Hampshire School of Law, New Hampshire's only law school; St.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Paul's School, a private preparatory school; NHTI, a two-year community college; the New Hampshire Police Academy; and the New Hampshire Fire Academy.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord's Old North Cemetery is the final resting place of Franklin Pierce, 14th President of the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Interstate 89 and Interstate 93 are the two main interstate highways serving the city, and general aviation access is via Concord Municipal Airport.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The nearest airport with commercial air service is Manchester–Boston Regional Airport, 23 miles (37 km) to the south.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] There has been no passenger rail service to Concord since 1981.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Historically, the Boston and Maine Railroad served the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The area that would become Concord was originally settled thousands of years ago by Abenaki Native Americans called the Pennacook.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The tribe fished for migrating salmon, sturgeon, and alewives with nets strung across the rapids of the Merrimack River.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The stream was also the transportation route for their birch bark canoes, which could travel from Lake Winnipesaukee to the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The broad sweep of the Merrimack River valley floodplain provided good soil for farming beans, gourds, pumpkins, melons and maize.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The area was first settled by Europeans in 1659 as Penacook, after the Abenaki word "pannukog" meaning "bend in the river," referencing the steep bends of the Merrimack River through the area.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] On January 17, 1725, the Province of Massachusetts Bay, which then claimed territories west of the Merrimack, granted the Concord area as the Plantation of Penacook.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] It was settled between 1725 and 1727 by Captain Ebenezer Eastman and others from Haverhill, Massachusetts.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] On February 9, 1734, the town was incorporated as "Rumford", from which Sir Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford, would take his title.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] It was renamed "Concord" in 1765 by Governor Benning Wentworth following a bitter boundary dispute between Rumford and the town of Bow; the city name was meant to reflect the new concord, or harmony, between the disputant towns.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Citizens displaced by the resulting border adjustment were given land elsewhere as compensation.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 1779, New Pennacook Plantation was granted to Timothy Walker Jr. and his associates at what would be incorporated in 1800 as Rumford, Maine, the site of Pennacook Falls.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord grew in prominence throughout the 18th century, and some of the earliest houses from this period survive at the northern end of Main Street.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 1808, Concord was named the official seat of state government, and in 1816 architect Stuart Park was commissioned to design a new capitol building for the state legislature on land sold to the state by local Quakers.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Construction on the State House was completed in 1819, and it remains the oldest capitol in the nation in which the state's legislative branches meet in their original chambers.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord was also named the seat of Merrimack County in 1823, and the Merrimack County Courthouse was constructed in 1857 in the North End at the site of the Old Town House.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Stephens Abbot to form Abbot and Downing.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Their most famous product was their Concord coach, widely used in the development of the American West, and their enterprise largely boosted and changed the city economy in the mid-19th century.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In subsequent years, Concord would also become a hub for the railroad industry, with Penacook a textile manufacturing center using water power from the Contoocook River.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city also around this time started to become a center for the emerging healthcare industry, with New Hampshire State Hospital opening in 1842 as one of the first psychiatric hospitals in the United States.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The State Hospital continued to expand throughout the following decades, and in 1891 Concord Hospital opened its doors as Margaret Pillsbury General Hospital, the first general hospital in the state of New Hampshire.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord's economy changed once again in the 20th century with the declining railroad and textile industry.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city developed into a center for national politics due to New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary, and many presidential candidates still visit the Concord area during campaign season.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Today, Concord remains a center for politics, law, healthcare, and insurance companies.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is located in south-central New Hampshire.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] It is 38 miles (61 km) north of the Massachusetts border, 40 miles (64 km) west of the Maine border, 54 miles (87 km) east of the Vermont border, and 170 miles (270 km) south of the Canadian border at Pittsburg.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 67.2 square miles (174.0 km2).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] 64.0 square miles (165.7 km2) of it are land and 3.2 square miles (8.4 km2) of it are water, comprising 4.81% of the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is drained by the Merrimack River.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Penacook Lake, the largest lake in the city and its main source of water, is in the west.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The highest point in Concord is 860 feet (260 m) above sea level on Oak Hill, just west of the hill's 970-foot (300 m) summit in neighboring Loudon.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord lies fully within the Merrimack River watershed and is centered on the river, which runs from northwest to southeast through the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Downtown is located on a low terrace to the west of the river, with residential neighborhoods climbing hills to the west and extending southwards towards the town of Bow.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] To the east of the Merrimack, atop a 100-foot (30 m) bluff, is a flat, sandy plain known as Concord Heights, which has seen most of the city's commercial development since 1960.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The eastern boundary of Concord (with the town of Pembroke) is formed by the Soucook River, a tributary of the Merrimack.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The Turkey River winds through the southwestern quarter of the city, passing through the campus of St.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Paul's School before entering the Merrimack River in Bow.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In the northern part of the city, the Contoocook River enters the Merrimack at the village of Penacook.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is 16 miles (26 km) north of Manchester, New Hampshire's largest city, and 66 miles (106 km) north of Boston.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city of Concord is made up of its downtown, including its North End and South End neighborhoods, plus the four distinct villages of Penacook, Concord Heights, East Concord, and West Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord, as with much of New England, is within the humid continental climate zone (Köppen *Dfb*), with long, cold, snowy winters, warm (and at times humid) summers, and relatively brief autumns and springs.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In winter, successive storms deliver moderate to at times heavy snowfall amounts, contributing to the relatively reliable snow cover.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In addition, lows reach below 0 °F (−18 °C) on an average 15 nights per year, and the city straddles the border between USDA Hardiness Zone 5b and 6a.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] However, thaws are frequent, with one to three days per month with 50 °F (10 °C)+ highs from December to February.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Summer can bring stretches of humid conditions as well as thunderstorms, and there is an average of 12 days of 90 °F (32 °C)+ highs annually.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The window for freezing temperatures on average begins on September 27 and expires on May 14.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The monthly daily average temperature range from 20.6 °F (−6.3 °C) in January to 70.0 °F (21.1 °C) in July.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Temperature extremes have ranged from −37 °F (−38 °C) in February 1943 to 102 °F (39 °C) in July 1966.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] As of the 2020 census, Concord had a population of 43,976 and a population density of 687.7 people per square mile (265.5 people/km2).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] 17.2% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.1% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] For every 100 females there were 100.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 100.0 males age 18 and over.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] 90.3% of residents lived in urban areas, while 9.7% lived in rural areas.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] There were 18,161 households in Concord, of which 23.9% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Of all households, 40.2% were married-couple households, 19.6% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.6% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] About 35.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] There were 19,085 housing units, of which 4.8% were vacant.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 4.2%.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] At the 2010 census there were 42,695 residents and 10,052 families in the city, as well as 18,852 housing units at an average density of 293.2 per square mile (113.2/km2).
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 2010 there were 17,592 households, out of which 28.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.3% were headed by married couples living together, 11.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 42.9% were non-families.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] 33.6% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.0% were someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The average household size was 2.26, and the average family size was 2.90.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In the city, the population was spread out, with 20.7% under the age of 18, 9.3% from 18 to 24, 28.0% from 25 to 44, 28.2% from 45 to 64, and 13.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] For every 100 females, there were 98.5 males.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 96.9 males.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] For the period 2019–2023, the median annual income for a household in the city was $83,701.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The per capita income for the city was $45,420.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] About 8.7% of those in Concord were below the poverty line during 2019–2023.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 2020, the top employer in the city remained the State of New Hampshire, with over 6,000 employed workers, while the largest private employer was Concord Hospital, with just under 3,000 employees.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Interstate 89 and Interstate 93 are the two main interstate highways serving Concord, and join just south of the city limits.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Interstate 89 links Concord with Lebanon and the state of Vermont to the northwest, while Interstate 93 connects the city to Plymouth, Littleton, and the White Mountains to the north and Manchester and Boston to the south.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Interstate 393 is a spur highway leading east from Concord and merging with U.S.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Route 4 as a direct route to New Hampshire's Seacoast region.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Route 3 serves as Concord's Main Street, while U.S.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Route 202 and New Hampshire Route 9 cross the city from east to west.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] State routes 13 and 132 also serve the city: Route 13 leads southwest out of Concord towards Goffstown and Milford, while Route 132 travels north parallel to Interstate 93.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] New Hampshire Route 106 passes through the easternmost part of Concord, crossing I-393 and NH 9 before crossing the Soucook River south into the town of Pembroke.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] To the north, NH 106 leads to Loudon, Belmont and Laconia.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Historically, Concord served as an important railroad terminal and station for the Boston and Maine Railroad.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The former Concord Station was located at what is now a Burlington department store on Storrs Street.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The station itself was built in 1860, but the fourth and most famous iteration of the station was built in 1885, which had a brick head house designed by Bradford L.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The head house was demolished in 1959 and replaced by a smaller "McGinnis Era" station.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] By 1967, all passenger rail services to Concord had been discontinued.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] For 13 months in 1980 and 1981, MBTA Commuter Rail ran two round trips a day between Boston and Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Since then, there has not been any passenger rail service to Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In 2021, Amtrak announced their plan to implement new service between Boston and Concord by 2035.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Local bus service is provided by Concord Area Transit (CAT), with three routes through the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Regional bus service provided by Concord Coach Lines and Greyhound Lines is available from the Concord Transportation Center at 30 Stickney Avenue next to Exit 14 on Interstate 93, with service south to Boston and points in between, as well as north to Littleton and northeast to Berlin.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] General aviation services are available through Concord Municipal Airport, located 2 miles (3 km) east of downtown.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] There is no commercial air service within the city limits; the nearest such airport is Manchester–Boston Regional Airport, 23 miles (37 km) to the south.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord's downtown underwent a significant renovation between 2015 and 2016, during the city's "Complete Streets Improvement Project".
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] At a proposed cost of $12 million, the project promised to deliver on categories of maintenance to aging infrastructure, improved accessibility, increased sustainability, a safer experience for walkers, bikers and motorists alike, and to stimulate economic growth in an increasingly idle downtown.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The main infrastructural change was reducing the four-lane street (two in each direction) to two lanes plus a turning lane in the center.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The freed-up space would contribute to extra width for bikes to ride in either direction, increased curb size and an added median where there is no need for a turning lane.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord opted to add shared lane markings for bikes, rather than a dedicated protected bike lane.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] By adding curb space, this project created new opportunities for pedestrians to enjoy the downtown.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Many power lines were buried, and street trees, colorful benches, art installations, and other green spaces were added, all allowing people to reclaim a space long dominated by cars.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Main Street underwent serious traffic calming, including a road diet, increased diagonal parking, widening sidewalks, adding shared lane markings, adding trees, texturing medians and coloring crosswalks red.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Another aspect of the new construction was adding heated sidewalk capabilities, utilizing excess steam from the local Concord Steam plant, and minimizing sand and snow blowing needed during the winter months.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Funding for Complete Streets came from a combination of $4,710,000 from a USDOT TIGER grant and the rest from the City of Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The project was initially proposed as costing $7,850,000, but ran over budget due to overambitious ideas.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] After scrapping some of the most expensive offenders, the budget ended up at $14.2 million, with the project actually coming in $1.1 million below that.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Although adding final aesthetic touches with the extra money were debated, the city council ended up deciding to save for financially straining years ahead.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The design was carried out by McFarland Johnson, IBI Group, and City of Concord Engineering.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is governed via the council-manager system.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city council consists of a mayor and 14 councilors, ten of which are elected to two-year terms representing each of the city wards, while the other four are elected at-large to four-year terms.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The mayor is elected directly every two years.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The current mayor as of 2026 is Byron Champlin, who was elected on November 4, 2025, with 62.6% of the vote.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] According to the Concord city charter, the mayor chairs the council, however has very few formal powers over the day-to-day management of the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The actual operations of the city are overseen by the city manager, currently Thomas J.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The current interim police chief is Barrett Moulton.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In the New Hampshire Senate, Concord is in the 15th District, represented by Democrat Tara Reardon.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] On the New Hampshire Executive Council, Concord is in the 2nd District, represented by Karen Liot Hill, the sole Democrat on the council.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] In the United States House of Representatives, Concord is in New Hampshire's 2nd congressional district, represented by Democrat Maggie Goodlander.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] New Hampshire Department of Corrections operates the New Hampshire State Prison for Men and New Hampshire State Prison for Women in Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord leans strongly Democratic in presidential elections; the last Republican nominee to carry the city was then Vice President George H.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Voter turnout was 72.7% in the 2020 general election, down from 76.2% in 2016, but still above the 2020 national turnout of 66.7%.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The city is otherwise served by Manchester area stations.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] New Hampshire Public Radio is headquartered in Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The New Hampshire State House, designed by architect Stuart Park and constructed between 1815 and 1818, is the oldest state house in which the legislature meets in its original chambers.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The building was remodeled in 1866, and the third story and west wing were added in 1910.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Across from the State House is the Eagle Hotel on Main Street, which has been a downtown landmark since its opening in 1827.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Grant, Rutherford Hayes, and Benjamin Harrison all dined there, and Franklin Pierce spent the night before departing for his inauguration.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Other well-known guests included Jefferson Davis, Charles Lindbergh, Eleanor Roosevelt, Richard M.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Nixon (who carried New Hampshire in all three of his presidential bids), and Thomas E.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] South from the Eagle Hotel on Main Street is Phenix Hall, which replaced "Old" Phenix Hall, which burned in 1893.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Both the old and new buildings featured multi-purpose auditoriums used for political speeches, theater productions, and fairs.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Abraham Lincoln spoke at the old hall in 1860; Theodore Roosevelt, at the new hall in 1912.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] North on Main Street is the Walker-Woodman House, also known as the Reverend Timothy Walker House, the oldest standing two-story house in Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] It was built for the Reverend Timothy Walker between 1733 and 1735.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] On the north end of Main Street is the Pierce Manse, in which President Franklin Pierce lived in Concord before and following his presidency.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The mid-1830s Greek Revival house was moved from Montgomery Street to North Main Street in 1971 to prevent its demolition.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Beaver Meadow Golf Course, located in the northern part of Concord, is one of the oldest golf courses in New England.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Besides this golf course, other important sporting venues in Concord include Everett Arena and Memorial Field.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The SNOB (Somewhat North Of Boston) Film Festival, started in the fall of 2002, brings independent films and filmmakers to Concord and has provided an outlet for local filmmakers to display their films.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] SNOB Film Festival was a catalyst for the building in 2007 of Red River Theatres, a locally owned, nonprofit, independent cinema named after the 1948 film featuring John Wayne.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord's public schools are within the Concord School District, except for schools in the Penacook area of the city, which are within the Merrimack Valley School District, a district which also includes several towns north of Concord.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The only public high school in the Concord School District is Concord High School, which had about 1,450 students as of Fall 2023.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The only public middle school in the Concord School District is Rundlett Middle School, which had roughly 770 students as of Fall 2023.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord School District's elementary schools underwent a major re-configuration in 2012, with three newly constructed schools opening and replacing six previous schools.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Beaver Meadow School, the remaining elementary school, was unaffected by the changes.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord schools in the Merrimack Valley School District include Merrimack Valley High School and Merrimack Valley Middle School, which are adjacent to each other and to Rolfe Park in Penacook village, and Penacook Elementary School, just south of the village.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord has two parochial schools, Bishop Brady High School and Saint John Regional School.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Other area private schools include Concord Christian Academy, Parker Academy, Trinity Christian School, and Shaker Road School.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Paul's School, a boarding school located in the city's West End neighborhood.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is home to New Hampshire Technical Institute, the city's primary community college, and Granite State College, which offers online two-year and four-year degrees.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] The University of New Hampshire School of Law is located near downtown, and the Franklin Pierce University Doctorate of Physical Therapy program also has a location in the city.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord Hospital recently announced plans to open a joint program with the New England College School of Nursing as part of their Bachelor of Nursing degree.
[src:concord-new-hampshire/concord-new-hampshire] Concord is also a major clinical site of Dartmouth College's Geisel School of Medicine, New Hampshire's only medical school.
